OVERWATCH_CODEX — Production Cost & Performance Audit
A. Executive Summary
Overall Risk Rating: MEDIUM
This is a well-engineered Streamlit-in-Snowflake monitoring app with many production-grade controls already in place. However, several patterns create hidden cost and performance exposure that must be addressed before sustained multi-user deployment.
Top 10 Issues Ranked by Business Impact
#	Issue	Impact
1	Shared warehouse (COMPUTE_WH) for app + business workloads	Cost attribution impossible; app queries compete with production work
2	INFORMATION_SCHEMA.QUERY_HISTORY() table function in Live Monitor scans up to 500 rows per fragment refresh every 15-30s	Potentially 120+ queries/hour per concurrent user
3	st.cache_data.clear() on global Refresh nukes ALL cached data for ALL users in the same SiS deployment	One user's refresh forces re-query for every concurrent session
4	No per-user session isolation in st.cache_data — cache keys include filter state but not user identity	Users with same filters share cache correctly, but cache invalidation is global
5	_cache_context() includes 10 session state fields as cache key — any change to any filter forces a complete cache miss	Over-granular cache keys cause unnecessary Snowflake queries
6	SQL string concatenation for filters (e.g., wh_clause, st_clause) rather than parameterized bindings	SQL injection partially mitigated by safe_sql() but f-string SQL still risks edge cases
7	No query result row LIMIT in most ACCOUNT_USAGE queries — only post-hoc _apply_result_guard() truncation	Full scan completes before the guard discards rows; credits already burned
8	Admin audit writes (log_admin_action) run on same warehouse — no isolation between observability writes and reads	Under load, audit INSERTs compete with dashboard reads
9	EXECUTE AS OWNER in snowflake.yml means the app runs with the deploying role's full privilege set	Over-permissioned by default; any code path has owner-role access to all granted objects
10	No connection pool or session reuse strategy across concurrent users in SiS	Each Streamlit user gets its own get_session() call chain; no session sharing or warm pool
Estimated Surprise-Cost Risk Areas
•	Live Monitor auto-refresh: 2-8 credits/day per active user (depending on XS vs S warehouse)
•	Global Refresh cache nuke on multi-user deployment: 5-20% wasted re-query credits
•	Unbounded date range queries (despite 35-day clamp): some SQL has hardcoded DATEADD('day', -N, ...) that ignores global filters
•	ALTER SESSION SET QUERY_TAG executes on every query when detailed tags enabled: 1 extra DDL roundtrip per query
